{"title_page": "Mary Fainsod Katzenstein", "text_new": "{{short description|American political scientist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Mary Fainsod Katzenstein\n| image             =\n| image_upright     = \n| alt               = \n| caption           =\n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = \n| death_date        = \n| death_place       =\n| nationality       = [[United States|American]]\n| fields            = {{ubl|[[Political science]]}}\n| alma_mater        = \n| workplaces        = \n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| doctoral_students = \n| known_for         = \n| awards            = {{ubl|[[Victoria Schuck Award]], [[American Political Science Association|APSA]]|Heinz I. Eulau Award, APSA|Frank Johnson Goodnow Award, APSA}}\n}}\n'''Mary Fainsod Katzenstein''' is an [[United States|American]] [[political scientist]]. She is the Stephen and Evalyn Milman Professor of American Studies, Emerita at [[Cornell University]]. She specializes in [[prison reform]] in the United States, the history of [[Feminism in the United States|American feminist activism]], and the [[politics of India]].\n\n==Career==\nBy 2015, the year of her retirement to emerita status, Katzenstein had published seven books and 39 articles.<ref name=cpep/> Katzenstein was the sole author of the 1979 book ''Ethnicity & Equality the Shiv Sena Party''. The book studies the conditions under which nativist ideas can be organized into coherent political movements, using the case of the [[Hindu nationalist]] [[Shiv Sena]] Party in 1960s [[India]].<ref>{{cite journal |first=Daniel R |last=Graves |title=Review Ethnicity and Equality: The Shiv Sena Party and Preferential Policies in Bombay. By Mary Fainsod Katzenstein. (Ithaca, N.Y.: Cornell University Press, 1979. Pp. 237. $15.00.) |journal=American Political Science Review |volume=74 |issue=2 |date=1 September 1980 |pages=843\u2013844 |doi=10.2307/1958205}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, Katzenstein published the book ''Faithful and Fearless: Moving Feminist Protest inside the Church and the Military''. In ''Faithful and Fearless'', Katzenstein demonstrates how the feminist protests of the 1960s in the United States, which began outside of official [[political institutions]], had by the 1990s transformed into a movement that largely took place inside the mainstream of American political institutions.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Laura R. |last=Woliver |title=Review Faithful and Fearless: Moving Feminist Protest Inside the Church and Military. By Mary Fainsod Katzenstein. Princeton, NJ: Princeton University Press, 1998. 270p. $40.00 cloth, $18.95 paper. |journal=American Political Science Review |volume=96 |issue=1 |date=3 March 2004 |pages=212 |doi=10.1017/S0003055402324328}}</ref> ''Faithful and Fearless'' won the 1999 Victoria Schuck Award from the [[American Political Science Association]],<ref name=vsa>{{cite web |title=Victoria Schuck Award |url=http://web.mnstate.edu/schwartz/AmerPoliSciAssocSchuck.html |publisher=Minnesota State University |year=2018 |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> which honors the best book published on the topic of women and politics each year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.apsanet.org/PROGRAMS/APSA-Awards/Victoria-Schuck-Award |title=Victoria Schuck Award |publisher=American Political Science Association |year=2019 |access-date=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2001 to 2002, Katzenstein was the recipient of a [[Russell Sage Foundation]] grant to study how federal government policy in the US has impacted the growth of prisons.<ref name=rsf>{{cite web |url=https://www.russellsage.org/visiting-scholars/mary-fainsod-katzenstein |title=Mary Fainsod Katzenstein |publisher=Russell Sage Foundation |year=2002 |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> The study included the effects of policies such as [[mandatory sentencing|mandatory minimum sentencing laws]] for the possession of certain drugs, or restricting access to [[Pell grants]].<Ref name=rsf/>\n\nVolumes that Katzenstein co-edited include ''Beyond Zero Tolerance; Discrimination and the Culture of the US Military'', with Judith Reppy (1999), and ''Social Movements in India: Poverty, Power, and Politics'', with [[Raka Ray]] (2005).<ref name=profile>{{cite web |url=https://government.cornell.edu/mary-fainsod-katzenstein |title=Mary Fainsod Katzenstein |publisher=Cornell University |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nKatzenstein's article \"The Dark Side of American Liberalism and Felony Disenfranchisement\", published with Leila Mohsen Ibrahim and Katherine Rubin in ''[[Perspectives on Politics]]'' in 2010, received the 2011 Heinz I. Eulau Award from the American Political Science Association for the best journal article published in ''Perspectives on Politics''.<ref name=eulau>{{cite web |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/american-political-science-association-announces-2011-awards-127605733.html |title=American Political Science Association Announces 2011 Awards |publisher=News Wire |date=12 August 2011 |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> Together with [[Minion K. C. Morrison]], Katzenstein also received the 2015 Frank Johnson Goodnow Award from the American Political Science Association, a lifetime award that \"honors service to the community of teachers, researchers, and public servants who work in the many fields of politics.\"<ref name=goodnow>{{cite web |url=https://www.apsanet.org/PROGRAMS/APSA-Awards/Frank-J-Goodnow-Award |title=Listing of all Recipients |publisher=American Political Science Association |year=2019 |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nKatzenstein has been a leader of the Cornell Prison Education Program and an instructor in that program,<ref name=cpep>{{cite web |url=https://news.cornell.edu/stories/2015/04/mary-katzenstein-honored-prison-education-program |title=Mary Katzenstein honored for prison education program |publisher=Cornell University |first=Linda B. |last=Glaser |date=27 April 2015 |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> which provides courses to inmates at prisons in [[Upstate New York]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cpep.cornell.edu/about-us/our-mission/ |title=Our Mission |publisher=Cornell Prison Education Program |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> Katzenstein has written articles in the public media about US prison reform, including pieces in the ''[[Boston Review]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=http://bostonreview.net/katzenstein-shanley-no-further-harm-incarcerated-fathers |title=What We Owe to Incarcerated Fathers |date=1 July 2008 |work=Boston Review |author1=Mary Fainsod Katzenstein |author2=Mary Lyndon Shanley |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> and ''[[The Washington Post]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2015/10/26/phone-calls-wont-cost-up-to-14-a-minute-anymore-but-heres-how-prisoners-families-are-still-being-fleeced/ |title=Phone calls won't cost up to $14 a minute anymore but here's how prisoners' families are still being fleeced |author1=Mary Fainsod Katzenstein |author2=Maureen Waller |date=26 October 2015 |work=The Washington Post |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> and her work on Indian politics has been cited in outlets like ''[[The Economic Times]]''<ref>{{cite news |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/balasaheb-thackeray-mumbais-godfather-was-once-a-man-of-bombay/articleshow/17272773.cms |title=Balasaheb Thackeray: Mumbai's godfather was once a man of Bombay |date=19 November 2012 |work=The Economic Times |last=Doctor |first=Vikram |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> and ''[[The Indian Express]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/research/shiv-sena-anniversary-52-bjp-hindutva-maharashtra-5224004/ |title=Shiv Sena's evolution: From Marathi Manoos to Hindutva, from with the BJP to without the BJP |date=19 June 2018 |work=The Indian Express |last=Roychowdhury |first=Adrija |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n*''Ethnicity & Equality the Shiv Sena Party'' (1979)\n*''Faithful and Fearless: Moving Feminist Protest inside the Church and the Military'' (1998)\n*''Beyond Zero Tolerance; Discrimination and the Culture of the US Military'', with Judith Reppy (1999)\n*''Social Movements in India: Poverty, Power, and Politics'', edited with Raka Ray (2005)\n\n==Selected awards==\n*Victoria Schuck Award, American Political Science Association (1999)<ref name=vsa/>\n*Russell Sage Foundation researcher (2001\u20132002)<ref name=rsf/>\n*Heinz I. Eulau Award, American Political Science Association (2011)<ref name=eulau/>\n*Frank Johnson Goodnow Award, American Political Science Association (2015)<ref name=goodnow/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Katzenstein, Mary Fainsod}}\n[[Category:American women academics]]\n[[Category:American political scientists]]\n[[Category:Women political scientists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Cornell University faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American political scientist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Mary Fainsod Katzenstein\n| image             =\n| image_upright     = \n| alt               = \n| caption           =\n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = \n| death_date        = \n| death_place       =\n| nationality       = [[United States|American]]\n| fields            = {{ubl|[[Political science]]}}\n| alma_mater        = \n| workplaces        = \n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| doctoral_students = \n| known_for         = \n| awards            = {{ubl|Victoria Schuck Award, [[American Political Science Association|APSA]]|Heinz I. Eulau Award, APSA|Frank Johnson Goodnow Award, APSA}}\n}}\n'''Mary Fainsod Katzenstein''' is an [[United States|American]] [[political scientist]]. She is the Stephen and Evalyn Milman Professor of American Studies, Emerita at [[Cornell University]]. She specializes in [[prison reform]] in the United States, the history of [[Feminism in the United States|American feminist activism]], and the [[politics of India]].\n\n==Career==\nBy 2015, the year of her retirement to emerita status, Katzenstein had published seven books and 39 articles.<ref name=cpep/> Katzenstein was the sole author of the 1979 book ''Ethnicity & Equality the Shiv Sena Party''. The book studies the conditions under which nativist ideas can be organized into coherent political movements, using the case of the [[Hindu nationalist]] [[Shiv Sena]] Party in 1960s [[India]].<ref>{{cite journal |first=Daniel R |last=Graves |title=Review Ethnicity and Equality: The Shiv Sena Party and Preferential Policies in Bombay. By Mary Fainsod Katzenstein. (Ithaca, N.Y.: Cornell University Press, 1979. Pp. 237. $15.00.) |journal=American Political Science Review |volume=74 |issue=2 |date=1 September 1980 |pages=843\u2013844 |doi=10.2307/1958205}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, Katzenstein published the book ''Faithful and Fearless: Moving Feminist Protest inside the Church and the Military''. In ''Faithful and Fearless'', Katzenstein demonstrates how the feminist protests of the 1960s in the United States, which began outside of official [[political institutions]], had by the 1990s transformed into a movement that largely took place inside the mainstream of American political institutions.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Laura R. |last=Woliver |title=Review Faithful and Fearless: Moving Feminist Protest Inside the Church and Military. By Mary Fainsod Katzenstein. Princeton, NJ: Princeton University Press, 1998. 270p. $40.00 cloth, $18.95 paper. |journal=American Political Science Review |volume=96 |issue=1 |date=3 March 2004 |pages=212 |doi=10.1017/S0003055402324328}}</ref> ''Faithful and Fearless'' won the 1999 Victoria Schuck Award from the [[American Political Science Association]],<ref name=vsa>{{cite web |title=Victoria Schuck Award |url=http://web.mnstate.edu/schwartz/AmerPoliSciAssocSchuck.html |publisher=Minnesota State University |year=2018 |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> which honors the best book published on the topic of women and politics each year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.apsanet.org/PROGRAMS/APSA-Awards/Victoria-Schuck-Award |title=Victoria Schuck Award |publisher=American Political Science Association |year=2019 |access-date=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2001 to 2002, Katzenstein was the recipient of a [[Russell Sage Foundation]] grant to study how federal government policy in the US has impacted the growth of prisons.<ref name=rsf>{{cite web |url=https://www.russellsage.org/visiting-scholars/mary-fainsod-katzenstein |title=Mary Fainsod Katzenstein |publisher=Russell Sage Foundation |year=2002 |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> The study included the effects of policies such as [[mandatory sentencing|mandatory minimum sentencing laws]] for the possession of certain drugs, or restricting access to [[Pell grants]].<Ref name=rsf/>\n\nVolumes that Katzenstein co-edited include ''Beyond Zero Tolerance; Discrimination and the Culture of the US Military'', with Judith Reppy (1999), and ''Social Movements in India: Poverty, Power, and Politics'', with [[Raka Ray]] (2005).<ref name=profile>{{cite web |url=https://government.cornell.edu/mary-fainsod-katzenstein |title=Mary Fainsod Katzenstein |publisher=Cornell University |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nKatzenstein's article \"The Dark Side of American Liberalism and Felony Disenfranchisement\", published with Leila Mohsen Ibrahim and Katherine Rubin in ''[[Perspectives on Politics]]'' in 2010, received the 2011 Heinz I. Eulau Award from the American Political Science Association for the best journal article published in ''Perspectives on Politics''.<ref name=eulau>{{cite web |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/american-political-science-association-announces-2011-awards-127605733.html |title=American Political Science Association Announces 2011 Awards |publisher=News Wire |date=12 August 2011 |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> Together with [[Minion K. C. Morrison]], Katzenstein also received the 2015 Frank Johnson Goodnow Award from the American Political Science Association, a lifetime award that \"honors service to the community of teachers, researchers, and public servants who work in the many fields of politics.\"<ref name=goodnow>{{cite web |url=https://www.apsanet.org/PROGRAMS/APSA-Awards/Frank-J-Goodnow-Award |title=Listing of all Recipients |publisher=American Political Science Association |year=2019 |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nKatzenstein has been a leader of the Cornell Prison Education Program and an instructor in that program,<ref name=cpep>{{cite web |url=https://news.cornell.edu/stories/2015/04/mary-katzenstein-honored-prison-education-program |title=Mary Katzenstein honored for prison education program |publisher=Cornell University |first=Linda B. |last=Glaser |date=27 April 2015 |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> which provides courses to inmates at prisons in [[Upstate New York]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cpep.cornell.edu/about-us/our-mission/ |title=Our Mission |publisher=Cornell Prison Education Program |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> Katzenstein has written articles in the public media about US prison reform, including pieces in the ''[[Boston Review]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=http://bostonreview.net/katzenstein-shanley-no-further-harm-incarcerated-fathers |title=What We Owe to Incarcerated Fathers |date=1 July 2008 |work=Boston Review |author1=Mary Fainsod Katzenstein |author2=Mary Lyndon Shanley |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> and ''[[The Washington Post]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2015/10/26/phone-calls-wont-cost-up-to-14-a-minute-anymore-but-heres-how-prisoners-families-are-still-being-fleeced/ |title=Phone calls won't cost up to $14 a minute anymore but here's how prisoners' families are still being fleeced |author1=Mary Fainsod Katzenstein |author2=Maureen Waller |date=26 October 2015 |work=The Washington Post |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> and her work on Indian politics has been cited in outlets like ''[[The Economic Times]]''<ref>{{cite news |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/balasaheb-thackeray-mumbais-godfather-was-once-a-man-of-bombay/articleshow/17272773.cms |title=Balasaheb Thackeray: Mumbai's godfather was once a man of Bombay |date=19 November 2012 |work=The Economic Times |last=Doctor |first=Vikram |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> and ''[[The Indian Express]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/research/shiv-sena-anniversary-52-bjp-hindutva-maharashtra-5224004/ |title=Shiv Sena's evolution: From Marathi Manoos to Hindutva, from with the BJP to without the BJP |date=19 June 2018 |work=The Indian Express |last=Roychowdhury |first=Adrija |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n*''Ethnicity & Equality the Shiv Sena Party'' (1979)\n*''Faithful and Fearless: Moving Feminist Protest inside the Church and the Military'' (1998)\n*''Beyond Zero Tolerance; Discrimination and the Culture of the US Military'', with Judith Reppy (1999)\n*''Social Movements in India: Poverty, Power, and Politics'', edited with Raka Ray (2005)\n\n==Selected awards==\n*Victoria Schuck Award, American Political Science Association (1999)<ref name=vsa/>\n*Russell Sage Foundation researcher (2001\u20132002)<ref name=rsf/>\n*Heinz I. Eulau Award, American Political Science Association (2011)<ref name=eulau/>\n*Frank Johnson Goodnow Award, American Political Science Association (2015)<ref name=goodnow/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Katzenstein, Mary Fainsod}}\n[[Category:American women academics]]\n[[Category:American political scientists]]\n[[Category:Women political scientists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American 